</div>
</div>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-expert-tips">Expert tips</h2>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-expect-the-topping-to-spread">Expect the topping to spread</h3>



<p>The pastry topping has some extra buttermilk beyond what I would use for drop biscuits so they flatten a bit during baking, creating the classic cobblestone appearance of a cobbler. For slightly drier biscuits that hold their shape better in the oven, you can reduce the buttermilk by 1 fluid ounce to 1 cup, or 8 fluid ounces.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-don-t-replace-the-blackberries">Don't replace the blackberries</h3>



<p>This filling is designed to let blackberries shine while adjusting for some of their limitations, and I don't recommend any other berries or fruit in their place. If you don't like blackberries, try my <a href="https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/gluten-free-blueberry-cobbler/" type="post" id="39091">gluten free blueberry cobbler</a> recipe or my <a href="https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/gluten-free-peach-cobbler/" type="post" id="25642">gluten free peach cobbler recipe</a> or even my <a href="https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/gluten-free-peach-crisp/">gluten free peach crisp recipe</a>. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1532" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201200%201532'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="overhead view of baked blackberry cobbler in a square white baking dish with a spoon in the berry filling" class="wp-image-88804" data-lazy-srcset="https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4.jpg 1200w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4-500x638.jpg 500w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4-860x1098.jpg 860w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4-117x150.jpg 117w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4-400x511.jpg 400w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4-150x192.jpg 150w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" data-lazy-src="https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1532" src="https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4.jpg" alt="overhead view of baked blackberry cobbler in a square white baking dish with a spoon in the berry filling" class="wp-image-88804" srcset="https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4.jpg 1200w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4-500x638.jpg 500w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4-860x1098.jpg 860w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4-117x150.jpg 117w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4-400x511.jpg 400w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-4-150x192.jpg 150w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></noscript></figure>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-ingredient-substitutions">Ingredient substitutions</h2>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-diary-free">Diary free</h3>



<p>In place of dairy butter, try block-style vegan butter like Miyoko's or Melt brands, or butter-flavored Spectrum shortening. In place of buttermilk, use half nondairy unsweetened milk with a similar consistency to cow's milk (like coconut milk in the carton or soy milk) and half nondairy sour cream or plain Greek-style yogurt, both by volume. Vegan butter will melt more quickly, so I'd recommend reducing your buttermilk sub by about 2 tablespoons for a firmer topping that can absorb more liquid. </p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-raspberries">Raspberries</h3>



<p>You can replace all of the raspberries with more blackberries, by weight, if you don't have or don't want to use raspberries. </p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-tapioca-starch">Tapioca starch</h3>



<p>If you don't have tapioca starch, I recommend superfine white rice flour (nothing gritty), or cornstarch. Cornstarch creates a cloudier, not clear, gel and has a greater tendency to weep or release liquid as it cools, but it can withstand high heat (unlike arrowroot or potato starch). </p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-no-buttermilk-on-hand">No buttermilk on hand</h3>



<p>If you can have dairy but just don't have buttermilk on hand, you can use half sour cream or plain Greek-style yogurt, half cow's milk (not fat free), by volume. You can also replace the buttermilk with as much plain lowfat or whole milk kefir without any other changes. </p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-full"><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1659" src="data:image/svg+xml,%3Csvg%20xmlns='http://www.w3.org/2000/svg'%20viewBox='0%200%201200%201659'%3E%3C/svg%3E" alt="serving dish of blackberry cobbler with mostly melted vanilla ice cream and a spoon, with more cobbler and fresh blackberries nearby" class="wp-image-88805" data-lazy-srcset="https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5.jpg 1200w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5-500x691.jpg 500w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5-860x1189.jpg 860w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5-108x150.jpg 108w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5-1111x1536.jpg 1111w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5-400x553.jpg 400w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5-150x207.jpg 150w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" data-lazy-src="https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5.jpg" /><noscript><img decoding="async" width="1200" height="1659" src="https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5.jpg" alt="serving dish of blackberry cobbler with mostly melted vanilla ice cream and a spoon, with more cobbler and fresh blackberries nearby" class="wp-image-88805" srcset="https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5.jpg 1200w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5-500x691.jpg 500w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5-860x1189.jpg 860w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5-108x150.jpg 108w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5-1111x1536.jpg 1111w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5-400x553.jpg 400w, https://glutenfreeonashoestring.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/Gluten-free-blackberry-cobbler-5-150x207.jpg 150w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></noscript></figure>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading" id="h-storage-instructions">Storage instructions</h2>



<p>I don't recommend assembling this dish before baking and serving it. It's best freshly prepared and baked. </p>



<p>Since the pastry topping is more fluffy than it is crispy, you can store completely cooled leftovers in a tightly sealed container at room temperature for up to 3 days. You can transfer it to a small, microwave-safe bowl and warm briefly in the microwave to loosen the filling a bit before serving, but it isn't essential. You can store it for up to 1 week in the refrigerator, but it will dry out a bit. </p>



<p>For longer storage, freeze individual portions in tightly sealed, freezer-safe containers and defrost at room temperature. </p>


